which are the following.

19:32.400 --> 19:35.840
One, there is such a thing as a general factor of cognitive ability

19:35.840 --> 19:37.760
on which human beings differ.

19:37.760 --> 19:41.280
Two, all standardized tests of academic aptitude or achievement

19:41.280 --> 19:43.680
measure this general factor to some degree,

19:43.680 --> 19:48.240
but IQ tests expressly designed for that purpose measure it most accurately.

19:48.240 --> 19:51.280
Three, IQ scores match, to a first degree,

19:51.280 --> 19:53.680
whatever it is that people mean when they use the word

19:53.680 --> 19:56.400
intelligent or smart in ordinary language.

19:56.960 --> 19:58.960
Four, IQ scores are stable,

19:58.960 --> 20:02.160
although not perfectly so over much of a person's life.

20:02.160 --> 20:05.680
Five, properly administered IQ tests are not demonstrably biased

20:05.680 --> 20:08.400
against social, economic, ethnic, or racial groups.

20:08.400 --> 20:11.760
And six, cognitive ability is substantially heritable,

20:11.760 --> 20:14.800
apparently no less than 40% and no more than 80%.

20:15.360 --> 20:16.400
And on that last point,

20:16.400 --> 20:18.880
Hans-Nina Murray later writes in a section titled

20:18.880 --> 20:21.120
How Much Is IQ a Matter of Genes?

20:21.120 --> 20:23.120
For purposes of this discussion,

20:23.120 --> 20:27.120
we will adopt a middling estimate of 60% heritability,

20:27.120 --> 20:32.960
which by extension means that IQ is about 40% a matter of environment.

20:32.960 --> 20:35.680
So, on to part one of the bell curve,

20:35.680 --> 20:38.720
which is titled The Emergence of a Cognitive Elite,

20:38.720 --> 20:40.880
and introduces Hans-Nina Murray's theory

20:40.880 --> 20:43.680
of the cognitive partitioning of society.

20:44.560 --> 20:46.240
Since World War II, they argue,

20:46.240 --> 20:50.560
colleges in the United States have increasingly admitted people by test score

20:50.560 --> 20:54.400
rather than things like social standing or familial connections.

20:54.400 --> 20:57.120
Where you could once expect to attend a prestigious college

20:57.120 --> 20:58.960
if your father had gone there, for instance,

20:58.960 --> 21:02.880
increasingly you now need to have competitive test scores.

21:02.880 --> 21:06.480
This has led to high IQ people being found disproportionately

21:06.480 --> 21:10.000
in the top institutions and geographically close together.

21:10.000 --> 21:13.440
The job market is also increasingly IQ focused,

21:13.440 --> 21:16.240
as low IQ jobs are replaced by automation,

21:16.240 --> 21:21.360
and the best jobs have apparently become more selective of high IQ candidates.

21:21.360 --> 21:25.680
IQ is also apparently a very good predictor of job performance.

21:25.680 --> 21:27.120
These high IQ people,

21:27.120 --> 21:31.280
economically and geographically segregated from the rest of society,

21:31.280 --> 21:33.600
are increasingly partnering with each other,

21:33.600 --> 21:36.640
and since we're assuming IQ is largely genetic,

21:36.640 --> 21:39.360
are producing high IQ offspring.

21:39.360 --> 21:45.120
Society is thus stratifying itself into some sort of intelligence-based caste system.

21:45.120 --> 21:46.080
At the end of part one,

21:46.080 --> 21:49.040
Hans-Nina Murray summarized their claims by saying,

21:49.040 --> 21:51.840
One, the cognitive elite is getting richer in an era

21:51.840 --> 21:54.640
when everyone else is having to struggle to stay even.

21:54.640 --> 21:58.640
Two, the cognitive elite is increasingly segregated physically from everyone else

21:58.640 --> 22:00.720
in both the workplace and the neighborhood.

22:00.720 --> 22:05.120
And three, the cognitive elite is increasingly likely to intermarry.

22:05.120 --> 22:06.880
Part two of the bell curve is titled

22:06.880 --> 22:09.280
Cognitive Classes and Social Behavior,

22:09.280 --> 22:11.520
and here, Hans-Nina Murray make the case that

22:11.520 --> 22:16.320
intelligence is tied to behavior and predictably determines various things,

22:16.320 --> 22:20.160
such as the likelihood of being poor, a criminal, a high school dropout,

22:20.160 --> 22:23.360
unemployed, an unwed mother, on welfare, and so on.

22:23.920 --> 22:25.200
In order to argue this,

22:25.200 --> 22:28.400
Hans-Nina Murray first introduced the source of their data,

22:28.400 --> 22:32.400
which is the Armed Forces Qualifying Test, or AFQT.

22:33.120 --> 22:39.120
This test was taken as part of the 1979 National Longitudinal Survey of Youth.

22:39.120 --> 22:42.320
The subjects of this survey were aged 14 to 22,

22:42.320 --> 22:46.080
and were administered the Armed Forces Qualifying Test in 1980.

22:46.560 --> 22:49.600
Researchers then interviewed the group over the following decade,

22:49.600 --> 22:52.320
asking them various questions about themselves.

22:52.320 --> 22:56.080
Hans-Nina Murray used the respondents' scores on the AFQT

22:56.080 --> 22:58.400
to determine the IQ of each person,

22:58.400 --> 23:01.920
and then used their later interview answers to calculate to what degree

23:01.920 --> 23:05.600
a high IQ is correlated with positive life outcomes,

23:05.600 --> 23:09.680
and to what degree a low IQ is correlated with negative outcomes.

23:09.680 --> 23:12.000
Throughout the rest of this section of the bell curve,

23:12.000 --> 23:14.640
Hans-Nina Murray go further than simply arguing

23:14.640 --> 23:18.640
for the correlation between low IQ and those negative life outcomes.

23:18.640 --> 23:22.960
They make the case that one's AFQT score correlates with them more strongly

23:22.960 --> 23:25.520
than socioeconomic status does.

23:25.520 --> 23:29.120
Hans-Nina Murray compare the AFQT scores of each respondent

23:29.120 --> 23:34.240
against their calculation of the socioeconomic status of the respondent's parents.

23:34.240 --> 23:37.600
So, as the book Inequality by Design puts it,

23:37.600 --> 23:40.480
roughly in the bell curve statistical comparisons,

23:40.480 --> 23:46.320
the parent's class represents nurture, and the AFQT score represents nature.

23:46.320 --> 23:48.480
Looking at various negative life outcomes,

23:48.480 --> 23:52.160
like being in poverty, being in jail, being unemployed, and so on,

23:52.160 --> 23:56.880
Hans-Nina Murray repeatedly find that for the young respondents to the survey,

23:56.880 --> 24:02.800
AFQT score and by proxy IQ score is a more accurate predictor of life outcomes

24:02.800 --> 24:05.440
than a parent's socioeconomic status.

24:05.440 --> 24:08.400
Hans-Nina Murray conclude this section by stating that

24:08.400 --> 24:11.040
a smarter population is more likely to be

24:11.040 --> 24:15.280
and more capable of being made into a civil citizenry.

24:15.280 --> 24:18.560
Part three of the bell curve is titled The National Context

24:18.560 --> 24:21.520
and is where things start getting especially controversial.

24:21.520 --> 24:24.240
This is the section of the book where they discuss differences

24:24.240 --> 24:28.000
in cognitive ability across designated racial groups.

24:28.000 --> 24:31.520
They review published literature on differences in racial IQ scores

24:31.520 --> 24:34.640
and find substantial differences between the various groups.

24:34.640 --> 24:37.040
They discuss the ways in which tests can be biased,

24:37.040 --> 24:39.440
culturally and otherwise, but ultimately conclude

24:39.440 --> 24:43.120
that these group differences cannot be explained away by bias.

24:43.120 --> 24:46.080
In chapter 15, Hans-Nina Murray talk about how they think

24:46.080 --> 24:49.360
cognitive ability in the West is declining, stating,

24:49.360 --> 24:52.560
Throughout the West, modernization has brought falling birth rates.

24:52.560 --> 24:56.160
The rates fall faster for educated women than the uneducated.

24:56.160 --> 24:59.440
Because education is so closely linked with cognitive ability,

24:59.440 --> 25:02.160
this tends to produce a dysgenic effect

25:02.160 --> 25:05.120
or a downward shift in the ability distribution.

25:05.120 --> 25:08.320
Furthermore, education leads women to have their babies later,

25:08.320 --> 25:12.160
which alone also produces additional dysgenic pressure.

25:12.160 --> 25:14.640
Have you ever seen the movie Idiocracy?

25:14.640 --> 25:16.800
Because this is just that, basically.

25:16.800 --> 25:20.240
Lower IQ people have more children than higher IQ people,

25:20.240 --> 25:24.160
so therefore average IQ scores are going down.

25:24.160 --> 25:26.800
However, Hans-Nina Murray run into a problem here,

25:26.800 --> 25:30.560
which is that IQ scores had been going up, not down,

25:30.560 --> 25:33.760
in the decades prior to the publication of the bell curve.

25:33.760 --> 25:35.760
This is known as the Flynn Effect,

25:35.760 --> 25:39.440
named for intelligence researcher James R. Flynn, who documented it,

25:39.440 --> 25:41.520
and we will talk more about the bell curve's attempt

25:41.520 --> 25:44.000
to account for the Flynn Effect later on.

25:44.000 --> 25:45.920
Part four of the bell curve is titled

25:45.920 --> 25:49.120
Living Together and is Concerned with Social Policy.

25:49.120 --> 25:52.640
This is where Hans-Nina Murray start proposing political solutions

25:52.640 --> 25:56.240
to the various problems they outlined in the previous chapters.

25:56.240 --> 25:58.960
They discuss, and ultimately brand as ineffective,

25:58.960 --> 26:03.040
all contemporary attempts to help disadvantaged children succeed in life.

26:03.600 --> 26:07.440
Things like better nutrition, better schooling, a better home environment,

26:07.440 --> 26:12.320
all these things can possibly, temporarily make people smarter, to a degree.

26:12.880 --> 26:16.320
But in the end, Hans-Nina Murray conclude that they will all eventually

26:16.320 --> 26:19.760
run into a genetic limit that cannot be worked around.

26:19.760 --> 26:23.760
Far more money is spent in ineffective attempts to help the disadvantaged

26:23.760 --> 26:26.720
than is spent on the gifted, Hans-Nina Murray contend,

26:26.720 --> 26:30.400
and we should thus directly shift the resources upwards

26:30.400 --> 26:32.560
to support our best and brightest.

26:32.560 --> 26:35.680
And this quote is from the introduction to Chapter 18.

26:35.680 --> 26:39.680
Some federal funds now so exclusively focused on the disadvantaged

26:39.680 --> 26:42.640
should be reallocated to programs for the gifted.

26:42.640 --> 26:46.880
Affirmative action in schools, as it stands, should be scrapped, of course.

26:46.880 --> 26:52.240
Hans-Nina Murray argue for a sort of race-blind, score-based affirmative action.

26:52.240 --> 26:56.560
They still support colleges accepting applicants from disadvantaged backgrounds,

26:56.560 --> 27:00.400
but only if they have comparable test scores to the other applicants.

27:00.400 --> 27:03.360
Affirmative action in the job market should also be scrapped,

27:03.360 --> 27:06.640
with Hans-Nina Murray arguing that in pursuit of equality,

27:06.640 --> 27:09.200
we have actually already overshot it,

27:09.200 --> 27:13.600
and that black people actually attain better quality jobs than white people,

27:13.600 --> 27:16.480
once you account for their IQs, of course.

27:16.480 --> 27:19.840
Hans-Nina Murray argue for encouraging low IQ parents

27:19.840 --> 27:22.560
to have fewer children in a couple of different ways.

27:23.200 --> 27:27.360
Firstly, they argue for making marriage a prerequisite for parental rights,

27:27.360 --> 27:30.960
and they also support cutting off welfare for low-income mothers,

27:30.960 --> 27:34.000
stating that we urge generally that these policies,

27:34.000 --> 27:37.520
represented by the extensive network of cash and services

27:37.520 --> 27:41.440
for low-income women who have babies, be ended.

27:41.440 --> 27:44.960
They also argue more generally in favor of individualism,

27:44.960 --> 27:47.200
concluding Chapter 21 by writing,

27:47.200 --> 27:52.240
Individualism is not only America's heritage, it must be its future.

27:52.240 --> 27:55.520
Hans-Nina Murray conclude this part of the bell curve with the following.

27:56.160 --> 27:59.840
Inequality of endowments, including intelligence, is a reality.

27:59.840 --> 28:04.160
Trying to pretend that inequality does not really exist has led to disaster.

28:04.160 --> 28:09.600
Trying to eradicate inequality with artificially manufactured outcomes has led to disaster.

28:09.600 --> 28:14.880
It is time for America to once again try living with inequality as life is lived,

28:14.880 --> 28:19.040
understanding that each human being has strengths and weaknesses and so on.

28:19.040 --> 28:22.080
This is the end of the main text of the bell curve.

28:22.080 --> 28:25.360
Then follows seven appendices explaining various things,

28:25.360 --> 28:29.520
about the data and statistical methods used in the book, among other things.

28:29.520 --> 28:33.760
Additionally, newer versions of the bell curve contain an afterword written in response

28:33.760 --> 28:38.240
to various criticisms directed at the book by various scientists and journalists,

28:38.240 --> 28:41.280
and we will be quoting from that at several points later on.

28:41.840 --> 28:44.000
So then, that was the bell curve.

28:44.000 --> 28:46.640
And before we carry on here, I think it would be worthwhile

28:46.640 --> 28:50.160
to attempt to summarize the general argument of the book.

28:50.160 --> 28:53.920
So here is my understanding of it in four points.

28:53.920 --> 28:57.360
One, general intelligence, or G, exists.

28:57.360 --> 29:00.800
General intelligence is to some degree heritable, innate,

29:00.800 --> 29:04.560
unable to be significantly changed and unevenly distributed,

29:04.560 --> 29:07.120
both within and across population groups.

29:08.000 --> 29:11.840
Two, IQ tests measure G fairly and accurately.

29:12.560 --> 29:16.480
Three, one's IQ is more important than one's social background

29:16.480 --> 29:18.720
in determining one's life outcomes.

29:19.280 --> 29:22.560
And four, given what we can learn from these points,

29:22.560 --> 29:25.360
we should implement conservative social policies,

29:25.360 --> 29:28.800
such as limiting welfare, incentivizing marriage,

29:28.800 --> 29:31.360
abandoning affirmative action, and more broadly,

29:31.360 --> 29:35.840
we should promote a return to a more individualistic society.

29:35.840 --> 29:39.280
Now, I'm sure someone could disagree with the conservative adjective

29:39.280 --> 29:41.600
in this last point and argue that Herrnstein and Murray

29:41.600 --> 29:45.520
merely promote whatever policies seem to best address the problems they discuss.

29:46.160 --> 29:48.960
They propose better access to birth control, for instance,

29:48.960 --> 29:51.840
which is not typically a conservative policy.

29:51.840 --> 29:54.320
Overall, though, their policy recommendations

29:54.320 --> 29:56.960
definitely lean heavily to the right.

29:56.960 --> 30:00.400
So it's now time to begin looking at the counter arguments,

30:00.400 --> 30:02.880
and we will begin with point one on this list

30:02.880 --> 30:05.520
and talk about general intelligence.

30:05.520 --> 30:08.160
So if we want to understand general intelligence,

30:08.160 --> 30:10.720
we first need to understand the statistical technique

30:10.720 --> 30:14.400
by which it is calculated, factor analysis.

30:14.400 --> 30:16.720
And if we want to understand factor analysis,

30:16.720 --> 30:20.320
we first need to talk about correlation and causation.

30:20.320 --> 30:22.400
Starting with correlation, then.

30:22.400 --> 30:26.720
Correlation is basically statistical association.

30:26.720 --> 30:29.040
Stephen Jay Gould in The Mismeasure of Man

30:29.040 --> 30:30.720
describes it in the following way.

30:31.520 --> 30:34.160
Correlation assesses the tendency of one measure

30:34.160 --> 30:36.400
to vary in concert with another.

30:36.400 --> 30:40.560
As a child grows, for example, both its arms and legs get longer.

30:40.560 --> 30:43.840
This joint tendency to change in the same direction

30:43.840 --> 30:45.680
is called a positive correlation.

30:46.240 --> 30:50.880
Not all parts of the body display such positive correlation during growth.

30:50.880 --> 30:54.160
Teeth, for example, do not grow after they erupt.

30:54.160 --> 30:57.520
The relationship between first incisor length and leg length

30:57.520 --> 31:02.000
from, say, age 10 to adulthood would represent zero correlation.

31:02.000 --> 31:05.520
Legs would get longer while teeth changed not at all.

31:05.520 --> 31:07.680
Other correlations can be negative.

31:07.680 --> 31:10.640
One measure increases while the other decreases.

31:10.640 --> 31:13.760
We begin to lose neurons at a distressingly early age

31:13.760 --> 31:15.360
and they are not replaced.

31:15.360 --> 31:18.480
Thus, the relationship between leg length and number of neurons

31:18.480 --> 31:21.920
after mid-childhood represents negative correlation.

31:21.920 --> 31:25.520
Leg length increases while number of neurons decreases.

31:25.520 --> 31:28.240
And Gould also includes this handy illustration

31:28.240 --> 31:30.880
of some example correlation graphs here.

31:30.880 --> 31:34.800
Now, of course, leg length and arm length are positively correlated

31:34.800 --> 31:37.200
because they share an underlying cause,

31:37.200 --> 31:40.320
which is simply general biological growth.

31:40.320 --> 31:42.240
However, we can think of plenty of things

31:42.240 --> 31:45.680
that are positively correlated and do not share a cause.

31:45.680 --> 31:48.080
You might be familiar with the following examples

31:48.080 --> 31:51.920
from the page Spurious Correlations, which I will link below.

31:51.920 --> 31:55.840
Per capita cheese consumption correlates with number of people who died

31:55.840 --> 31:57.920
by becoming tangled in their bedsheets.

31:58.560 --> 32:02.240
Number of letters in winning word of Scripps National Spelling Bee

32:02.240 --> 32:06.960
correlates with number of people killed by venomous spiders, and so on.

32:06.960 --> 32:09.600
Obviously, these things have nothing to do with each other.

32:10.160 --> 32:11.120
Probably.

32:11.120 --> 32:13.520
So some correlations are just chance.

32:13.520 --> 32:16.880
It would be an error to assume a shared cause there.

32:16.880 --> 32:20.960
Correlation does not imply causation, is the saying.

32:20.960 --> 32:25.040
Now, in addition to assuming a shared cause when there is not one,

32:25.040 --> 32:29.600
another common mistake here is to ignore a shared cause when there is one.

32:29.600 --> 32:32.240
For example, when considering arm and leg length

32:32.240 --> 32:34.960
to ignore the underlying biological growth

32:34.960 --> 32:39.600
and assume that legs are getting longer because arms are, or vice versa.

32:39.600 --> 32:43.600
There are lots of different ways to misrepresent correlations, basically.

32:43.600 --> 32:48.800
I agree with Gould when he writes the invalid assumption that correlation implies cause

32:48.800 --> 32:54.240
is probably among the two or three most serious and common errors of human reasoning.

32:54.240 --> 32:58.800
Anyway, one result of us calculating the correlation between arm and leg lengths

32:58.800 --> 33:01.920
is that we have simplified the data somewhat.

33:01.920 --> 33:07.520
The strong correlation between the two variables means we can basically express them as one,

33:07.600 --> 33:11.520
so long as we don't mind losing a little information along the way.

33:11.520 --> 33:14.000
But what if instead of just two variables,

33:14.000 --> 33:19.680
we wanted to compare correlations between the size of, say, 50 different body parts?

33:19.680 --> 33:23.200
Plotting two measurements in a graph is fairly easy.

33:23.200 --> 33:27.680
With the addition of a third measurement, though, things start getting a little trickier.

33:27.680 --> 33:32.320
This figure from the Mismeasure of Man, where Gould introduces head measurements into the mix,

33:32.320 --> 33:36.320
needs another dimension in order to convey the information.

33:36.320 --> 33:40.320
And with more variables added in, the data quickly gets too complex

33:40.320 --> 33:43.040
to display with a mere three dimensions.

33:43.040 --> 33:45.760
And this brings us to factor analysis.

33:45.760 --> 33:49.680
Similar to how we simplified arm and leg length to a single dimension,

33:50.240 --> 33:55.440
factor analysis can be used to reduce a complex system of correlated variables

33:55.440 --> 33:58.880
to a smaller number of underlying factors.

33:58.880 --> 34:03.360
And you might find that just a few underlying factors explain the vast majority of the

34:03.360 --> 34:06.480
variations in a larger number of variables.

34:06.480 --> 34:11.440
And furthermore, you could identify which factor explained the majority of the variation.

34:12.080 --> 34:15.760
I won't be going into the exact specifics of how factor analysis works.

34:16.480 --> 34:21.040
I couldn't if I wanted to, to be honest, but this is basically how it is used.

34:21.040 --> 34:22.240
To quote Gould again,

34:22.240 --> 34:27.680
factor analysis is a mathematical technique for reducing a complex system of correlations

34:27.680 --> 34:29.280
into fewer dimensions.

34:29.840 --> 34:34.080
So you might be wondering, what does all this have to do with intelligence?

34:34.080 --> 34:40.160
Well, factor analysis is how psychologist Charles Spearman came up with the concept of the G factor.

34:40.720 --> 34:45.600
Spearman looked at a big mass of data showing that people scores on various intelligence tests

34:45.600 --> 34:49.760
were positively correlated, carried out a little factor analysis,

34:49.760 --> 34:53.920
and identified the most important underlying statistical factor.

34:53.920 --> 34:57.360
He then called this G, or general intelligence.

34:57.360 --> 35:03.840
So this G is the underlying general mental ability that we are supposedly measuring with IQ tests.

35:03.840 --> 35:07.440
However, there are a few problems with this G factor.

35:07.440 --> 35:10.000
One is, as the bell curve itself points out,

35:10.000 --> 35:14.800
that it's based on statistical analysis rather than direct observation.

35:14.800 --> 35:20.000
We are inferring its existence from the data rather than measuring it directly, basically.

35:20.000 --> 35:23.280
It is the result of a particular statistical method.

35:24.000 --> 35:28.000
Secondly, simplifying the majority of the data down to a single factor

35:28.000 --> 35:31.200
can actually obscure a lot of useful information.

35:31.200 --> 35:35.760
What if the data shows that people who do well on tests of numerical ability

35:35.760 --> 35:39.280
tend to do well on other tests of numerical ability,

35:39.280 --> 35:42.320
and people who do well on tests of their language ability

35:42.320 --> 35:46.000
tend to do better on other tests of language ability?

35:46.000 --> 35:51.120
We can imagine two people who are determined to be statistically as smart as each other,

35:51.120 --> 35:54.880
but who excel in completely different areas, right?

35:54.880 --> 35:57.600
And there are several different intelligence theories

35:57.600 --> 36:00.720
identifying different clusters of mental abilities.

36:00.720 --> 36:04.320
Verbal, logical, spatial, mathematical, whatever else.

36:04.320 --> 36:08.000
You can go and read about all of those if you're very bored.

36:08.000 --> 36:12.720
But what can we take away from our little chat about correlation and factor analysis here?

36:12.720 --> 36:17.680
Well, first of all, factor analysis tells us nothing about causation.

36:17.680 --> 36:19.840
It deals with correlations.

36:19.840 --> 36:24.240
It can show that there might be common factors underlying different variables,

36:24.240 --> 36:30.240
but it does not identify for us why those variables vary.

36:30.240 --> 36:35.360
As a comparison here, let's say you take a sample of 10,000 random members of the public

36:35.360 --> 36:39.360
and you test their athletic performance at various physical tests.

36:39.360 --> 36:44.240
Amount of weight lifted, length jumped, speed at running various distances,

36:44.240 --> 36:46.000
sit-ups completed, whatever.

36:46.640 --> 36:51.840
And let's say that what you find is that people who perform well on one test relative to the group

36:51.840 --> 36:55.360
tend to perform well on the other tests relative to the group

36:55.360 --> 36:57.760
and vice versa for those who perform poorly.

36:58.400 --> 37:02.560
Now you could, if you so fancied, subject this data to factor analysis.

37:02.560 --> 37:07.280
Identify numerically the most important underlying factor and name it F

37:07.280 --> 37:09.600
for general fitness or something.

37:09.600 --> 37:14.560
And you could probably further assign each person an FQ or fitness quotient.

37:14.560 --> 37:20.240
However, what you would not have done is explain why some people are fitter than others.

37:20.240 --> 37:24.080
You would have said nothing about the heritability of athletic performance,

37:24.080 --> 37:28.480
the degree to which genetics and environment contribute to athletic performance.

37:28.480 --> 37:32.320
You'd have said nothing about the causes of the data at all.

37:32.320 --> 37:37.520
It would be a leap of logic to assume that each person's FQ is innate and unchangeable.

37:37.520 --> 37:41.440
The data you have cannot tell you any such thing by itself.

37:41.440 --> 37:45.280
You may also find that your singular numerical fitness quotient

37:45.280 --> 37:47.760
obscures a lot of useful information.

37:47.760 --> 37:51.520
For instance, you might find people who are better at strength exercises

37:51.520 --> 37:54.800
tend to be better at other strength exercises and so on.

37:54.800 --> 37:58.320
So the mere existence of a general factor of cognitive ability

37:58.320 --> 38:01.600
would not explain why there are differences between people.

38:02.240 --> 38:05.280
In fact, the G factor is perfectly consistent

38:05.280 --> 38:10.000
with a 100% environmental approach to understanding intelligence.

38:10.000 --> 38:12.240
We could play devil's advocate here and say,

38:12.240 --> 38:16.480
yes, a general factor of intelligence exists and is important,

38:16.480 --> 38:22.320
but the variance in G between people is explained entirely by environmental factors.

38:22.320 --> 38:27.360
Childhood nutrition, socioeconomic status, school quality, and so on.

38:27.360 --> 38:30.640
Absolutely nothing happens in the factor analysis process

38:30.640 --> 38:36.240
to tell us about what the causes are for people having different measurable levels of intelligence.

38:36.320 --> 38:40.240
And even if we accept a single general intelligence factor exists,

38:40.240 --> 38:44.400
that would not necessarily imply a genetic causation.

38:44.400 --> 38:48.960
And speaking of genetics, let's next talk about the word heritability.

38:49.600 --> 38:50.960
When the bell curve says,

38:50.960 --> 38:53.760
cognitive ability is substantially heritable,

38:53.760 --> 38:56.800
apparently no less than 40% and no more than 80%,

38:57.680 --> 38:59.360
what does that mean exactly?

38:59.360 --> 39:02.320
If we average it for 60%, like they do,

39:02.320 --> 39:05.920
are we therefore to assume that each person's individual IQ

39:05.920 --> 39:11.200
is 60% determined by heritable genetics and 40% by the environment?

39:12.000 --> 39:13.680
Well, no.

39:13.680 --> 39:16.960
Heritability is unfortunately one of those awkward words

39:16.960 --> 39:21.200
which has a common use understanding and a scientific understanding

39:21.200 --> 39:23.840
which differ in a few important ways.

39:23.840 --> 39:26.240
The common use understanding is something like

39:26.240 --> 39:30.160
the ability of a thing to be passed down genetically, right?

39:30.160 --> 39:33.360
You can inherit being tall or having red hair,

39:33.360 --> 39:38.240
but you can't inherit a scar or a finger lost in an accident, say.

39:38.240 --> 39:42.320
The technical academic meaning of heritability is rather different.

39:42.320 --> 39:45.760
Heritability is a numerical concept used to estimate

39:45.760 --> 39:51.440
the contribution of genetic variance to overall variance of a trait within a group.

39:51.440 --> 39:54.720
So basically, heritability estimates the degree to which

39:54.720 --> 39:59.440
the variance of a trait within a group is due to genetics.

39:59.440 --> 40:02.160
Height is thus a heritable trait.

40:02.160 --> 40:05.680
Taller parents will generally have taller offspring, for example,

40:05.680 --> 40:08.560
and this is measurable against a population group.

40:09.360 --> 40:13.680
Having two arms, however, is not a heritable trait

40:13.680 --> 40:16.720
because almost everyone has two arms.

40:16.720 --> 40:18.960
And for people who don't have two arms,

40:18.960 --> 40:22.400
that variance is usually environmental in nature.

40:22.400 --> 40:25.520
Having two arms is genetically determined,

40:25.520 --> 40:28.320
but it is not a heritable trait if you follow

40:28.320 --> 40:31.440
because genes account for very little of the variance

40:31.440 --> 40:33.360
within the population group.

40:33.360 --> 40:35.520
Something that is very highly heritable,

40:35.520 --> 40:38.320
we would say has a heritability of one.

40:38.320 --> 40:40.320
Something that is not heritable at all,

40:40.320 --> 40:42.720
we would say has a heritability of zero.

40:43.360 --> 40:46.640
If we say something has a heritability of 0.6,

40:46.640 --> 40:50.960
then what we mean there is that 60% of the variance of the trait

40:50.960 --> 40:54.720
in a population group will be due to genetic factors.

40:55.280 --> 40:59.760
What it does not mean is that 60% of the trait in one individual

40:59.760 --> 41:04.000
is due to their genes and 40% due to the environment.

41:04.000 --> 41:07.440
Heritability tells us about variance within a group,

41:08.080 --> 41:10.480
not the makeup of individuals.

41:10.480 --> 41:12.560
It is a population statistic.

41:12.560 --> 41:17.040
You cannot meaningfully ask what the heritability of your IQ is.

41:17.040 --> 41:18.400
So where am I going with this?

41:18.400 --> 41:21.040
Well, there's a couple of points that I'd like to make.

41:21.040 --> 41:24.640
The first is that a trait can be determined by your genes

41:24.640 --> 41:28.880
and be very lowly heritable, such as the presence of arms,

41:28.880 --> 41:30.560
and also the inverse of that.

41:30.560 --> 41:33.120
A trait could be very highly heritable

41:33.120 --> 41:36.240
and not directly genetically determined.

41:36.240 --> 41:39.600
One common example used to illustrate this is earrings.

41:40.240 --> 41:42.400
What would we say accounts for the variance

41:42.400 --> 41:45.520
in whether people wear earrings within a particular group?

41:46.080 --> 41:48.080
Well, depending on the group,

41:48.080 --> 41:51.040
most of the variance could be due, in one sense,

41:51.040 --> 41:54.160
to a genetic factor, biological sex.

41:54.640 --> 41:57.920
Wearing earrings would therefore be a heritable trait,

41:57.920 --> 42:00.720
but this does not mean that there is an earring gene

42:00.720 --> 42:03.040
that is being passed down generationally.

42:03.040 --> 42:05.920
The majority of people wearing earrings being women

42:05.920 --> 42:10.160
would be due to environmental factors, fashion and gender roles,

42:10.160 --> 42:12.240
which are subject to change over time.

42:12.800 --> 42:14.560
In more recent years, for example,

42:14.560 --> 42:17.840
men in the West have increasingly been wearing earrings.

42:17.840 --> 42:22.480
The heritability of the trait of wearing earrings is thus decreasing,

42:22.480 --> 42:26.480
because less of the variance is being accounted for by genetics.

42:26.480 --> 42:27.680
But crucially here,

42:27.680 --> 42:32.000
nothing is actually happening genetically on the earring front.

42:32.000 --> 42:36.720
The change in heritability is down to changing environmental factors.

42:36.720 --> 42:39.360
When we say something is due to genetics,

42:39.360 --> 42:42.720
we need to be very careful about exactly what we mean.

42:42.720 --> 42:44.960
A useful categorization here is

42:44.960 --> 42:48.720
direct versus indirect genetic determination.

42:48.720 --> 42:51.280
We need to be sure to differentiate between things

42:51.280 --> 42:54.160
that are directly genetically determined,

42:54.160 --> 42:58.160
as in your genes are directly causing some biochemical process

42:58.160 --> 42:59.440
to happen within you,

42:59.440 --> 43:02.400
and things that are indirectly genetically determined,

43:02.400 --> 43:06.320
as a result of your genes interacting with your environment.

43:06.320 --> 43:08.960
Women being more likely to wear earrings, for instance,

43:08.960 --> 43:10.640
is a heritable trait,

43:10.640 --> 43:14.000
but it is not directly genetically determined.

43:14.000 --> 43:17.840
This is relevant to us because IQ could be such a trait,

43:17.840 --> 43:20.960
where differences in IQ across designated racial groups

43:20.960 --> 43:24.240
are caused not by a direct genetic process,

43:24.240 --> 43:27.840
but instead by how our genetically determined characteristics

43:27.840 --> 43:30.000
interact with our environment,

43:30.000 --> 43:33.520
so as to affect our results on IQ tests.

43:33.520 --> 43:34.240
For example,

43:34.240 --> 43:38.320
let's imagine your genes cause you to have a particular skin color,

43:38.320 --> 43:40.560
and you live in a segregated society

43:40.560 --> 43:43.920
in which people with that skin color are discriminated against

43:43.920 --> 43:46.560
and do not have equal access to education.

43:47.120 --> 43:49.760
Now that group's lower results on IQ tests

43:49.760 --> 43:52.960
would be, in one sense, because of their genes.

43:52.960 --> 43:55.200
And scientists studying genetics

43:55.200 --> 43:57.520
might very well find a strong correlation

43:57.520 --> 44:01.520
between particular genes and lowered IQ test results,

44:01.520 --> 44:04.800
but if we don't take the environment into account,

44:04.800 --> 44:07.440
that by itself can't tell us anything.

44:07.440 --> 44:10.720
The point here is that a trait could be very highly heritable

44:10.720 --> 44:13.360
and correlated strongly with particular genes

44:13.360 --> 44:17.040
and still have zero direct genetic determination.

44:17.040 --> 44:19.040
Now the idea that wearing earrings

44:19.040 --> 44:22.080
can be more of a heritable trait than having ears

44:22.080 --> 44:25.520
is admittedly a bit of a difficult concept to grasp at first sight,

44:25.520 --> 44:27.600
and I would understand if it took a little time

44:27.600 --> 44:29.920
for someone to wrap their head around all this.

44:29.920 --> 44:32.720
Right now, though, what I want you to take away from this section,

44:32.720 --> 44:33.600
if nothing else,

44:33.600 --> 44:36.400
is the idea that something being heritable

44:36.400 --> 44:41.680
does not necessarily mean it is actually being directly caused by genetics.

44:41.680 --> 44:45.840
My next point is that heritability estimates the causes of variants

44:45.840 --> 44:46.960
within a group.

44:47.520 --> 44:52.000
It cannot tell us about reasons for differences across groups.

44:52.000 --> 44:53.040
And to illustrate this,

44:53.040 --> 44:57.360
we will paraphrase a thought experiment by geneticist Richard Lewontin.

44:57.360 --> 44:59.360
Let's say we take a packet of seeds

44:59.360 --> 45:03.520
and plant them in fertilized soil in a controlled laboratory environment,

45:03.520 --> 45:06.000
and we ensure that the growing plants have sufficient

45:06.000 --> 45:08.800
and equal amounts of water and light.

45:08.800 --> 45:10.800
And doesn't that sound nice?

45:10.800 --> 45:15.040
Now height in plants is a heritable trait, just like in humans,

45:15.040 --> 45:18.720
and the plants would thus grow to a range of different heights.

45:18.720 --> 45:22.560
Height in this experiment would be very highly heritable,

45:22.560 --> 45:26.400
because the fact we're ensuring the plants have an equal environment

45:26.400 --> 45:29.200
means that the variance in heights in the group

45:29.200 --> 45:31.440
is solely down to genetics.

45:31.440 --> 45:33.920
Next, let's say we do that experiment again,

45:33.920 --> 45:36.560
only this time we plant the seeds in bad soil

45:36.560 --> 45:41.440
and give them less but equal within the group amounts of water and light.

45:41.440 --> 45:45.440
The thing to understand here is that height in this second experiment

45:45.440 --> 45:49.440
would be exactly as heritable as in the previous experiment.

45:50.000 --> 45:54.240
All of the plants from the second group have the same group environment,

45:54.240 --> 45:56.960
meaning that, again, the group variance in heights

45:56.960 --> 45:59.360
would be solely down to genetics.

45:59.360 --> 46:02.480
The poor environment will produce smaller plants,

46:02.480 --> 46:06.160
but since they are all subject to that environment equally,

46:06.160 --> 46:08.240
heritability remains high.

46:08.240 --> 46:12.400
The problems arise when we start trying to compare these two groups.

46:12.400 --> 46:15.200
Let's say the second group of plants has an average height

46:15.200 --> 46:18.880
that is 15% shorter than the first group, for instance.

46:18.880 --> 46:23.200
The heritability of height tells us nothing about why that is.

46:23.200 --> 46:26.240
Heritability was the same across both groups.

46:26.240 --> 46:30.320
If you're trying to figure out why one group of plants grew larger than the other,

46:30.320 --> 46:34.400
saying height is heritable tells us nothing useful.

46:34.400 --> 46:38.720
The difference between the groups was entirely down to environmental factors,

46:38.720 --> 46:43.040
and heritability, despite being high, played no part.

46:43.040 --> 46:45.920
The two points we can take from this thought experiment are,

46:45.920 --> 46:50.560
firstly, the heritability of traits does not account for group differences,

46:50.560 --> 46:54.160
and secondly, a trait having a high heritability

46:54.160 --> 46:59.120
does not mean that trait is immutable or unaffected by the environment.

46:59.120 --> 47:03.520
For another example of this, height in humans is a highly heritable trait,

47:03.520 --> 47:07.360
but the average human height increased substantially over the last century,

47:07.360 --> 47:09.680
and this was due to environmental changes,

47:09.680 --> 47:12.160
such as better health care and nutrition.

47:12.160 --> 47:13.600
Or for another example,

47:13.600 --> 47:18.080
North Koreans are, on average, a few inches shorter than South Koreans,

47:18.080 --> 47:22.480
and this is down to the different material conditions in those two countries,

47:22.480 --> 47:26.000
not some recent radical divergence in genetics.

47:26.000 --> 47:28.960
Height is heritable in both North and South Korea,

47:28.960 --> 47:33.280
but it's the environment that is the cause of the variance between the groups.

47:33.840 --> 47:37.120
This is something that the bell curve crucially misunderstands

47:37.120 --> 47:41.120
when talking about the heritability of intelligence and IQ.

47:41.120 --> 47:42.880
On page 109, they say,

47:42.880 --> 47:47.200
even a heritability of 0.6 leaves room for considerable change

47:47.200 --> 47:50.720
if the changes in environments are commensurably large,

47:50.720 --> 47:53.680
the implication here being that higher heritabilities

47:53.680 --> 47:56.960
would be less affected by changes in the environment,

47:56.960 --> 47:59.200
and this is just not how it works.

47:59.200 --> 48:01.440
IQ could be 100% heritable

48:01.440 --> 48:04.720
and still massively affected by changes in the group environment.

48:04.720 --> 48:07.680
Professor Ned Block from New York University

48:07.680 --> 48:10.160
makes several of these points about heritability

48:10.160 --> 48:14.320
in an article entitled How Heritability Misleads About Race,

48:14.320 --> 48:15.520
and then goes on to say,

48:15.520 --> 48:19.120
I hope these points remove the temptation exhibited in the bell curve

48:19.120 --> 48:23.840
to think of the heritability of IQ as a constant, like the speed of light.

48:23.840 --> 48:26.400
Heritability is a population statistic,

48:26.400 --> 48:28.640
just like birth rate or number of TVs,

48:28.640 --> 48:32.160
and can be expected to change with changing circumstances.

48:32.160 --> 48:35.920
These issues are pathetically misunderstood by Charles Murray.

48:35.920 --> 48:38.960
In a CNN interview reported in the New Republic,

48:38.960 --> 48:40.000
Murray declared,

48:40.000 --> 48:43.600
when I, when we, say 60% heritability,

48:43.600 --> 48:46.080
it's not 60% of the variation,

48:46.080 --> 48:50.080
it is 60% of the IQ in any given person.

48:50.080 --> 48:52.720
Later, he repeated that for the average person,

48:52.720 --> 48:56.320
60% of the intelligence comes from heredity,

48:56.320 --> 48:59.520
and added that this was true of the human species,

48:59.520 --> 49:03.040
missing the point that heritability makes no sense for an individual

49:03.040 --> 49:06.480
and that heritability statistics are population relative.

49:06.480 --> 49:09.600
So if you don't quite understand all this stuff about heritability,

49:09.600 --> 49:13.840
don't feel too bad because Charles Murray doesn't understand it either.

49:13.840 --> 49:16.240
Or at least he didn't 25 years ago,

49:16.240 --> 49:18.960
he may have done his homework since then, who knows.

49:18.960 --> 49:22.320
Looking again at the bell curve's list of claims about intelligence,

49:22.320 --> 49:27.760
the only one on here that could be said to be making a point about genetics is number six.

49:27.760 --> 49:31.040
Cognitive ability is substantially heritable.

49:31.040 --> 49:32.240
However, as we've seen,

49:32.240 --> 49:37.360
a trait being heritable does not necessarily mean a direct genetic cause.

49:37.360 --> 49:42.400
It does not tell us anything about the heritability of a particular individual's intelligence,

49:42.400 --> 49:46.880
and it cannot tell us the reason for differences between groups of people.

49:46.880 --> 49:51.200
Those differences between people could be caused by environmental factors,

49:51.200 --> 49:55.520
because, twist, environments are heritable too.

49:55.520 --> 49:57.680
As the bell curve itself points out,

49:57.680 --> 50:01.520
non-genetic characteristics can nonetheless run in families.

50:01.520 --> 50:05.440
For practical purposes, environments are heritable too.

50:06.000 --> 50:07.680
So to summarize this section,

50:07.680 --> 50:12.080
we have considered the method by which a general intelligence factor is determined,

50:12.080 --> 50:14.800
and also claims about its heritability.

50:14.800 --> 50:17.200
But we can conclude from neither of these things

50:17.200 --> 50:22.640
that the variance in intelligence between groups of people has a direct genetic cause.

50:22.640 --> 50:25.920
The cause could simply be directly due to the environment,

50:25.920 --> 50:30.160
or indirectly by way of how genes are interacting with that environment.

50:30.720 --> 50:32.960
So why am I listing off all the ways in which

50:32.960 --> 50:38.400
Hanstein and Murray do not prove a genetic cause for cognitive ability, you might ask.

50:38.400 --> 50:41.680
Their later comparisons of IQ and environmental factors

50:41.680 --> 50:45.040
assume that IQ is largely genetic in origin,

50:45.040 --> 50:48.640
so presumably they do prove it at some point, right?

50:48.640 --> 50:51.040
Well, to put it bluntly, no.

50:51.040 --> 50:54.160
In their section, How Much Is IQ a Matter of Genes?,

50:54.160 --> 50:58.720
they estimate the heritability of IQ scores by talking about twin studies.

50:59.280 --> 51:04.400
We can use studies of identical twins, non-identical twins, and regular siblings

51:04.400 --> 51:07.600
to estimate the extent of genetic effects upon IQ

51:07.600 --> 51:13.120
by noting the differences in correlations between their scores on intelligence tests.

51:13.120 --> 51:15.520
However, there are a few problems with this.

51:15.520 --> 51:18.800
Most importantly for us here being that in attempting to learn about

51:18.800 --> 51:22.560
genetic cognitive ability via intelligence test scores,

51:22.560 --> 51:25.280
we have to make the assumption that intelligence tests

51:25.280 --> 51:28.320
are an accurate measure of cognitive ability.

51:28.320 --> 51:30.240
But more on that in a moment.

51:30.240 --> 51:35.360
Even if we assume that the tests do give an accurate representation of cognitive ability,

51:35.360 --> 51:40.400
attempts to use these correlations to construct a simple genetic model for IQ

51:40.400 --> 51:41.920
run into several issues.

51:42.480 --> 51:46.560
Firstly, the IQs of identical twins do not perfectly correlate,

51:46.560 --> 51:50.400
as we would expect them to, given their nearly identical genetics.

51:50.400 --> 51:53.280
The correlation of siblings who were raised apart is weaker

51:53.280 --> 51:56.240
than the correlation of siblings who were raised together.

51:56.240 --> 52:00.080
And probably most troublesome for a purely genetic model here

52:00.080 --> 52:05.280
is that there is also some correlation between parents and adopted children.

52:05.280 --> 52:07.360
Their scores correlate to some degree,

52:07.360 --> 52:13.120
despite there being no immediate genetic link beyond being the same species, of course.

52:13.120 --> 52:17.440
So in our search for exactly how much genetics affects cognitive ability,

52:17.440 --> 52:20.960
these observations are only ever going to get us so far.

52:20.960 --> 52:26.320
It's very difficult to disentangle the genetic effects from the environmental ones.

52:26.320 --> 52:30.080
What we really need here is genetics research to advance to the point

52:30.080 --> 52:33.680
where we understand exactly which genes influence intelligence

52:33.680 --> 52:36.080
and to which degree they influence intelligence.

52:36.720 --> 52:39.920
When the bell curve was published, the evidence was not there.

52:39.920 --> 52:41.760
As Herndstein and Murray admit,

52:41.760 --> 52:45.360
the state of knowledge does not permit a precise estimate.

52:45.360 --> 52:50.240
And in 2019, 25 years later, the evidence is still not there.

52:50.240 --> 52:52.960
If anything, with regards to the claims in the bell curve,

52:52.960 --> 52:55.760
particularly its claims about racial differences,

52:55.760 --> 52:59.040
the genetic story has only gotten more complicated.

52:59.040 --> 53:04.240
The reason I say designated racial groups instead of racial groups during this video

53:04.240 --> 53:06.000
is because on a genetic level,

53:06.000 --> 53:10.560
our skin color folk understanding of racial groups can be unhelpful.

53:10.560 --> 53:12.720
There can be greater genetic differences

53:12.720 --> 53:16.480
within our socially constructed racial groups than between them.

53:16.480 --> 53:20.960
I doubt anyone would be so naive as to expect us to one day identify

53:20.960 --> 53:25.440
the singular gene that controls both skin color and intelligence.

53:26.000 --> 53:31.200
Someone having dark skin and thus being identified and identifying as black

53:31.200 --> 53:33.840
could have a whole range of genetic history.

53:33.840 --> 53:37.840
You can't read someone's genes by looking at their skin color.

53:37.840 --> 53:41.120
This is important for us because the authors of the bell curve

53:41.120 --> 53:44.720
use our socially constructed racial groups in their book.

53:44.720 --> 53:46.480
Talking about this, they say,

53:46.480 --> 53:49.760
what does it mean to be black in America in racial terms

53:49.760 --> 53:52.720
when the word black or African-American can be used

53:52.720 --> 53:56.400
for people whose ancestry is more European than African?

53:56.400 --> 53:59.680
How are we to classify a person whose parents hail from Panama

53:59.680 --> 54:02.480
but whose ancestry is predominantly African?

54:02.480 --> 54:05.040
Is he a Latino, a black?

54:05.600 --> 54:08.160
The rule we follow here is to classify people

54:08.160 --> 54:11.600
according to the way they classify themselves.

54:11.600 --> 54:15.200
It would be a leap of logic to assume genetic explanations

54:15.200 --> 54:18.640
for characteristics of self-identified groups,

54:18.640 --> 54:22.560
given that those groups could have a wide range of genetic makeups.

54:22.560 --> 54:25.600
My point with all this is that the bell curve's direct evidence

54:25.600 --> 54:28.880
of a genetic basis for IQ is missing.

54:28.880 --> 54:31.360
Charles Murray's attitude towards this problem

54:31.440 --> 54:33.760
in the years since the publication of the book

54:33.760 --> 54:36.160
has been to kick the can down the road,

54:36.160 --> 54:39.840
assuming that he and Herrnstein were prematurely right,

54:39.840 --> 54:42.880
to borrow a phrase from his afterword to the bell curve,

54:42.880 --> 54:46.880
and that the accumulating genetic evidence will prove him right

54:46.880 --> 54:49.760
if everyone just waits a little longer.

54:49.760 --> 54:53.120
And it remains his tactic more than two decades later.

54:53.120 --> 54:55.920
In October of this year, Professor Ewan Birney,

54:55.920 --> 54:59.200
the director of the European Bioinformatics Institute,

54:59.200 --> 55:00.960
published a blog post titled

55:00.960 --> 55:04.240
Race, Genetics and Pseudoscience, an explainer,

55:04.240 --> 55:06.000
which discusses, among other things,

55:06.000 --> 55:08.480
how our traditional racial categorizations

55:08.480 --> 55:12.160
are not reflected in actual patterns of genetic variation,

55:12.160 --> 55:16.160
how distinct groups within Africa can be as distinct from each other

55:16.160 --> 55:18.080
as they are with non-Africans,

55:18.080 --> 55:22.240
how race is not a useful or accurate term for geneticists,

55:22.240 --> 55:25.520
and it says that it is often suggested that geneticists

55:25.520 --> 55:28.400
who emphasize the biological invalidity of race

55:28.400 --> 55:31.200
are under the form of political correctness,

55:31.200 --> 55:33.360
forced to suppress their real opinions

55:33.360 --> 55:36.560
in order to maintain their positions in the academy.

55:36.560 --> 55:38.800
Such accusations are unfounded

55:38.800 --> 55:42.560
and betray a lack of understanding of what motivates science.

55:42.560 --> 55:46.080
Charles Murray responded to this post on Twitter a few days later,

55:46.080 --> 55:46.640
saying,

55:46.640 --> 55:50.000
I can't understand why people are so eager to go public

55:50.000 --> 55:53.440
with positions for which the weight of the accumulating evidence

55:53.440 --> 55:54.800
is so unwelcome

55:54.800 --> 55:58.640
and that will be definitively settled within a few years.

55:58.640 --> 56:03.680
So it seems the evidence for Murray is still just a few years away.

56:03.680 --> 56:05.840
With regards to the bell curve, however,

56:05.840 --> 56:08.480
it is possible we are being a little unfair

56:08.480 --> 56:11.440
when we criticize it for basing much of its analysis

56:11.440 --> 56:13.520
on relatively crude estimations.

56:14.080 --> 56:16.800
After all, they do admit the evidence is not there,

56:16.800 --> 56:17.520
and they say,

56:17.520 --> 56:21.600
if the reader is now convinced that either the genetic or environmental explanation

56:21.600 --> 56:23.760
has won out to the exclusion of the other,

56:23.760 --> 56:27.600
we have not done a sufficiently good job of presenting one side or the other.

56:28.240 --> 56:31.040
We should not criticize scientists for saying,

56:31.040 --> 56:34.480
the evidence isn't there yet, but here's a rough guess.

56:34.480 --> 56:37.520
Presenting such estimates and attempting to disprove them

56:37.520 --> 56:39.840
is a key part of the scientific process.

56:40.480 --> 56:44.720
Problems arise when we get to part four of the bell curve, however.

56:44.720 --> 56:46.320
While it is fine to say,

56:46.320 --> 56:49.520
the evidence isn't there yet, but here's a rough guess,

56:49.520 --> 56:51.280
it is not so fine to say,

56:51.280 --> 56:53.120
the evidence isn't there yet,

56:53.120 --> 56:54.560
here's a rough guess.

56:54.560 --> 56:56.320
And based upon this rough guess,

56:56.320 --> 56:59.280
you should immediately suspend welfare programs

56:59.280 --> 57:01.440
for underprivileged children.

57:01.440 --> 57:03.120
But we'll talk more about this later

57:03.120 --> 57:05.600
when we discuss the politics of the bell curve.

57:05.600 --> 57:08.400
For now, though, let's address the assumption I mentioned earlier

57:08.400 --> 57:10.240
when talking about twin studies.

57:10.240 --> 57:11.760
We have been in this section

57:11.760 --> 57:15.440
assuming that we can measure native intelligence accurately.

57:15.440 --> 57:17.920
If we cannot measure native intelligence accurately,

57:17.920 --> 57:21.040
then much of what we've talked about thus far is irrelevant.

57:21.040 --> 57:24.400
So it's now time to talk about IQ tests.

57:24.400 --> 57:28.000
So I summarized the bell curve's claims about IQ tests

57:28.000 --> 57:32.160
as IQ tests measure G fairly and accurately.

57:32.160 --> 57:34.400
I wrote fairly because of their statement,

57:34.400 --> 57:37.680
properly administered IQ tests are not demonstrably biased

57:37.680 --> 57:40.720
against social, economic, ethnic, or racial groups.

57:40.720 --> 57:43.520
And I wrote the word accurately because of their statement

57:43.520 --> 57:46.880
that all standardized tests of academic aptitude or achievement

57:46.880 --> 57:49.200
measure this general factor to some degree,

57:49.200 --> 57:52.560
but IQ tests expressly designed for that purpose

57:52.560 --> 57:54.640
measure it most accurately.

57:54.640 --> 57:56.480
So firstly here, we're going to discuss

57:56.480 --> 57:59.600
a few of the possible problems with IQ tests,

57:59.600 --> 58:01.200
starting with the various ways

58:01.200 --> 58:03.840
in which they can deliver biased results.

58:03.840 --> 58:07.120
Now, direct cultural bias in IQ test items

58:07.120 --> 58:10.400
is discussed by Herrnstein and Murray in chapter 13.

58:10.400 --> 58:13.920
They use an example of a question that includes the word regata,

58:13.920 --> 58:16.160
which is a word that might bias the results

58:16.160 --> 58:19.280
towards certain cultural and economic groups.

58:19.280 --> 58:22.880
And certain historical so-called intelligence test questions

58:22.880 --> 58:24.720
have actually been much worse than this.

58:25.280 --> 58:29.040
Some of them amounted to nothing more than general knowledge questions.

58:29.040 --> 58:31.600
The army alpha test used in World War I

58:31.600 --> 58:33.440
asked army recruits to identify

58:33.440 --> 58:36.320
what particular celebrities were famous for,

58:36.320 --> 58:39.440
in which cities certain cars were manufactured,

58:39.440 --> 58:42.320
and the products produced by certain brands.

58:42.320 --> 58:45.120
Questions like these obviously have very little to do

58:45.120 --> 58:47.280
with any native intellectual ability,

58:47.280 --> 58:48.800
they're just testing whether or not

58:48.800 --> 58:51.760
you happen to already know the answer.

58:51.760 --> 58:54.160
There's no opportunity to work it out,

58:54.160 --> 58:57.600
so any psychometricians constructing intelligence tests

58:57.600 --> 58:58.880
certainly need to be careful

58:58.880 --> 59:02.400
to not include biased test items like these ones.

59:02.400 --> 59:05.360
Tests can also be biased for instruction.

59:05.360 --> 59:07.440
And what do we mean by instruction here?

59:07.440 --> 59:09.680
Well, simply whether or not you've been taught

59:09.680 --> 59:10.800
the meaning of a word

59:10.800 --> 59:13.520
or the best method for solving a maths problem

59:13.520 --> 59:15.200
is going to matter a lot on a test

59:15.200 --> 59:17.680
that requires you to draw upon your mathematical

59:17.680 --> 59:19.200
and language abilities.

59:19.200 --> 59:20.480
As an example here,

59:20.480 --> 59:22.400
I'm gonna assume that we all agree

59:22.400 --> 59:25.120
it would be unfair to expect a random teenager

59:25.120 --> 59:27.840
to, by themselves, during a test,

59:27.840 --> 59:29.760
invent trigonometry.

59:29.760 --> 59:31.920
If you include trigonometry questions

59:31.920 --> 59:33.520
on your intelligence test,

59:33.520 --> 59:34.880
what you'll be testing for there

59:34.880 --> 59:37.760
will not solely be the intelligence of the respondent,

59:37.760 --> 59:39.680
but also whether or not they've been taught

59:39.680 --> 59:41.280
trigonometry before,

59:41.280 --> 59:43.200
how recently they were taught it,

59:43.280 --> 59:45.360
and how well they were taught it.

59:45.360 --> 59:46.880
This is relevant for us here

59:46.880 --> 59:49.200
because the Armed Forces Qualifying Test,

59:49.200 --> 59:52.240
which is the primary source of intelligence test data

59:52.240 --> 59:53.280
in the bell curve,

59:53.280 --> 59:55.040
had as one of its four sections

59:55.040 --> 59:57.440
a mathematics test which included questions

59:57.440 --> 01:00:01.120
examining knowledge of classroom trigonometry and algebra.

01:00:01.120 --> 01:00:04.000
This is more of a test of scholastic aptitude

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:05.520
than native intelligence,

01:00:05.520 --> 01:00:07.280
and is also testing by proxy

01:00:07.280 --> 01:00:10.080
the quality of the teaching at the different schools

01:00:10.080 --> 01:00:12.240
that the AFQT respondents went to.

01:00:12.800 --> 01:00:14.480
We can't assume that to be equal

01:00:14.480 --> 01:00:16.960
across thousands of different people, can we?

01:00:16.960 --> 01:00:19.440
This is one of a few problems with the AFQT

01:00:19.440 --> 01:00:20.720
that has roots in the fact

01:00:20.720 --> 01:00:23.280
that it was not designed as an IQ test,

01:00:23.280 --> 01:00:25.120
but more on that in a second.

01:00:25.120 --> 01:00:28.640
Another way that IQ tests can be biased is for speed.

01:00:28.640 --> 01:00:30.720
Think of the definitions of intelligence

01:00:30.720 --> 01:00:31.840
we've seen so far.

01:00:31.840 --> 01:00:35.120
A capacity for complex mental work,

01:00:35.120 --> 01:00:37.440
catching on, making sense of things,

01:00:37.440 --> 01:00:39.440
and figuring out what to do.

01:00:39.440 --> 01:00:41.680
And simply because of the way IQ tests

01:00:41.680 --> 01:00:42.480
are administered,

01:00:42.480 --> 01:00:43.920
we have to add the words

01:00:43.920 --> 01:00:46.800
within the time constraints of an academic test

01:00:46.800 --> 01:00:48.320
to all of those things.

01:00:48.320 --> 01:00:50.160
IQ tests are by their nature

01:00:50.160 --> 01:00:52.480
biased towards how fast you can think

01:00:52.480 --> 01:00:54.560
and away from other important qualities

01:00:54.560 --> 01:00:57.280
which contribute to overall cognitive ability

01:00:57.280 --> 01:01:00.720
such as stamina, determination, and discipline.

01:01:00.720 --> 01:01:01.760
Similar to that point,

01:01:01.760 --> 01:01:03.920
IQ tests have a more general bias

01:01:03.920 --> 01:01:07.280
towards familiarity with an academic environment.

01:01:07.280 --> 01:01:09.440
People unfamiliar with taking tests

01:01:09.440 --> 01:01:10.720
are going to fare worse

01:01:10.720 --> 01:01:12.560
than people who are very used to it

01:01:12.560 --> 01:01:15.600
simply due to being in an unfamiliar environment.

01:01:15.600 --> 01:01:17.760
Things like anxiety and stress

01:01:17.760 --> 01:01:19.040
come into play here.

01:01:19.040 --> 01:01:21.120
Those can affect intelligence test results

01:01:21.120 --> 01:01:22.800
despite having nothing directly

01:01:22.800 --> 01:01:24.960
to do with intelligence themselves.

01:01:24.960 --> 01:01:26.000
Herrnstein and Murray

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:28.480
are particularly aware of that last point,

01:01:28.480 --> 01:01:29.760
and we need to briefly discuss

01:01:29.760 --> 01:01:31.280
the Flynn effect here.

01:01:31.280 --> 01:01:33.360
So when IQ tests are constructed,

01:01:33.360 --> 01:01:36.560
they're standardized using a sample of test takers.

01:01:36.560 --> 01:01:38.000
Now what that means in practice

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:40.080
is the testers will test some people,

01:01:40.080 --> 01:01:41.760
work out the average score,

01:01:41.760 --> 01:01:44.560
and set that to correspond to 100.

01:01:44.560 --> 01:01:48.800
This is why we recognize an IQ of 100 as the average.

01:01:48.800 --> 01:01:51.040
When those IQ tests are later revised

01:01:51.040 --> 01:01:53.360
or when new IQ tests are designed,

01:01:53.360 --> 01:01:55.840
they're also standardized on new groups of people

01:01:55.840 --> 01:01:58.640
and their average is set again to 100.

01:01:59.200 --> 01:02:00.720
However, researchers noticed

01:02:00.720 --> 01:02:02.160
that when newer test subjects

01:02:02.160 --> 01:02:04.400
take the older versions of a test,

01:02:04.400 --> 01:02:07.520
their IQ scores are on average higher.

01:02:07.520 --> 01:02:10.640
So IQ scores have gone up over time, basically,

01:02:10.640 --> 01:02:14.160
meaning if you believe that IQ tests measure intelligence,

01:02:14.160 --> 01:02:17.440
then people must be getting more intelligent, right?

01:02:17.440 --> 01:02:19.440
This is troublesome for Herrnstein and Murray

01:02:19.440 --> 01:02:21.120
because they argue the opposite,

01:02:21.120 --> 01:02:23.840
that cognitive ability is deteriorating.

01:02:23.840 --> 01:02:25.360
And this brings us back to our point

01:02:25.360 --> 01:02:28.160
about bias towards an academic environment.

01:02:28.160 --> 01:02:29.520
Addressing the Flynn effect,

01:02:29.520 --> 01:02:31.680
Herrnstein and Murray write the following.

01:02:31.680 --> 01:02:33.520
There is a further question to answer.

01:02:33.520 --> 01:02:35.360
Does a 15-point IQ difference

01:02:35.360 --> 01:02:37.440
between grandparents and their grandchildren

01:02:37.440 --> 01:02:40.320
mean that the grandchildren are 15 points smarter?

01:02:40.320 --> 01:02:43.200
Some experts do not believe that the rise is holy,

01:02:43.200 --> 01:02:46.240
perhaps not even partly a rise in intelligence,

01:02:46.240 --> 01:02:47.840
but in the narrower skills

01:02:47.840 --> 01:02:51.040
involved in intelligence test-taking per se.

01:02:51.040 --> 01:02:52.240
So this, if it were true,

01:02:52.240 --> 01:02:55.520
would mean that people are actually getting less intelligent,

01:02:55.520 --> 01:02:56.960
but at the same time,

01:02:56.960 --> 01:03:00.240
they are getting better at taking IQ tests.

01:03:00.240 --> 01:03:03.520
Now, you might say, isn't that a huge contradiction?

01:03:03.520 --> 01:03:05.920
Aren't they basically admitting that IQ tests

01:03:05.920 --> 01:03:09.200
measure something other than inborn intelligence?

01:03:09.200 --> 01:03:12.000
After all, if IQ tests supposedly measure

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:14.400
native cognitive ability accurately,

01:03:14.400 --> 01:03:16.160
how could scores be going up

01:03:16.160 --> 01:03:18.800
while cognitive ability is going down?

01:03:18.800 --> 01:03:20.960
However, to be fair to Herrnstein and Murray,

01:03:20.960 --> 01:03:22.800
it would be hasty to dismiss

01:03:22.800 --> 01:03:25.440
their dysgenics hypothesis outright.

01:03:25.440 --> 01:03:27.520
There is another possibility here,

01:03:27.520 --> 01:03:31.040
and it's that people are getting genetically less intelligent,

01:03:31.040 --> 01:03:33.920
but the environmental factors affecting intelligence

01:03:33.920 --> 01:03:36.320
have undergone such large changes

01:03:36.320 --> 01:03:38.800
that their positive effects upon IQ

01:03:38.800 --> 01:03:40.160
are more than accounting

01:03:40.160 --> 01:03:42.720
for the downward genetic ability shift.

01:03:42.720 --> 01:03:46.000
So roughly, we would have lost a genetic IQ point

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:47.280
thanks to dysgenics,

01:03:47.280 --> 01:03:50.880
but gained two back thanks to a better environment.

01:03:50.880 --> 01:03:53.120
So what evidence does the bell curve produce

01:03:53.120 --> 01:03:55.040
in support of this downward trend

01:03:55.040 --> 01:03:57.200
in genetic cognitive ability?

01:03:57.200 --> 01:03:59.600
Well, unfortunately for Herrnstein and Murray,

01:03:59.600 --> 01:04:01.040
their main source of data,

01:04:01.040 --> 01:04:03.680
the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth,

01:04:03.680 --> 01:04:05.120
is not much use here.

01:04:05.760 --> 01:04:08.800
Ideally, what we want to do is give IQ tests

01:04:08.800 --> 01:04:12.000
to the children of women who took part in the AFQT,

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:14.880
so we could directly compare child to parent

01:04:14.880 --> 01:04:17.600
and see if any downwards shift was happening.

01:04:17.600 --> 01:04:19.280
However, this would be a mistake,

01:04:19.280 --> 01:04:20.720
as since our data is coming

01:04:20.720 --> 01:04:24.000
from the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth,

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:26.800
the respondents are, appropriately, young.

01:04:27.360 --> 01:04:29.440
People who wait longer to have children

01:04:29.440 --> 01:04:32.160
are typically wealthier and better educated,

01:04:32.160 --> 01:04:35.280
and thus tend to have children with higher IQs.

01:04:35.280 --> 01:04:38.560
Limiting ourselves to looking at only young mothers

01:04:38.560 --> 01:04:42.880
will skew the apparent IQ of the next generation downwards,

01:04:42.880 --> 01:04:45.040
so it would be an inaccurate thing to do.

01:04:45.600 --> 01:04:47.440
Herrnstein and Murray are, thankfully,

01:04:47.440 --> 01:04:48.960
well aware of this problem.

01:04:49.840 --> 01:04:52.880
Not that it stops them from trying, however.

01:04:52.880 --> 01:04:55.440
Herrnstein and Murray's dysgenics hypothesis

01:04:55.520 --> 01:04:59.040
is discussed in Intelligence, Genes, and Success,

01:04:59.040 --> 01:05:01.520
Scientists Respond to the Bell Curve,

01:05:01.520 --> 01:05:05.600
a 1997 book which responds to many of the points

01:05:05.600 --> 01:05:07.040
made in the Bell Curve.

01:05:07.040 --> 01:05:08.960
The authors of that book, for their part,

01:05:08.960 --> 01:05:11.120
find no direct empirical evidence,

01:05:11.120 --> 01:05:13.680
either for or against a dysgenic effect

01:05:13.680 --> 01:05:15.760
acting upon cognitive ability,

01:05:15.760 --> 01:05:18.320
stating that, insofar as we are aware,

01:05:18.320 --> 01:05:21.920
there is nothing but anecdotal evidence for dysgenics.

01:05:21.920 --> 01:05:23.920
Anyway, let's get back on track.

01:05:23.920 --> 01:05:27.280
Now, to illustrate another way IQ tests can be biased,

01:05:27.280 --> 01:05:29.360
I think it would be a good exercise for us all

01:05:29.360 --> 01:05:33.600
to briefly take a very simple one-question test together.

01:05:33.600 --> 01:05:36.240
So get your pencil and paper ready, folks.

01:05:36.240 --> 01:05:36.880
Here it is.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:39.200
Easy, right?

01:05:39.200 --> 01:05:42.320
An incredibly simple number sequence question there,

01:05:42.320 --> 01:05:45.440
the sort you'd expect nearly anyone to be able to work out.

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:49.040
It's also a fair and unbiased question, of course.

01:05:49.040 --> 01:05:51.920
I mean, everyone was given the exact same question

01:05:51.920 --> 01:05:54.960
and the exact same amount of time to answer it, right?

01:05:54.960 --> 01:05:58.080
What could be more fair and unbiased than that?

01:05:58.080 --> 01:06:00.320
Now, of course, this question is not fair.

01:06:00.320 --> 01:06:03.760
It is biased in favor of Japanese people.

01:06:03.760 --> 01:06:05.920
And anime fans, I guess.

01:06:05.920 --> 01:06:08.000
The point here is that this question would,

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:10.400
in any language, be biased against people

01:06:10.400 --> 01:06:12.640
who don't speak that language.

01:06:12.640 --> 01:06:14.960
A question in English is biased against people

01:06:14.960 --> 01:06:17.120
who don't speak English, isn't it?

01:06:17.120 --> 01:06:18.400
Now you might protest.

01:06:18.400 --> 01:06:20.480
This seems like a very obvious point.

01:06:20.480 --> 01:06:24.240
I mean, surely nobody is gonna give an IQ test in English

01:06:24.240 --> 01:06:26.880
to a group of people who are not fluent in English

01:06:26.880 --> 01:06:30.000
and then try to pass off those results as legitimate, right?

01:06:30.640 --> 01:06:32.880
Well, stay tuned, folks.

01:06:32.880 --> 01:06:35.840
One point not given due consideration by the bell curve

01:06:35.840 --> 01:06:38.000
during their discussion of testing bias

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:41.120
is that even a completely unbiased test,

01:06:41.120 --> 01:06:43.760
were it possible to construct such a thing,

01:06:43.760 --> 01:06:46.080
would still deliver biased results

01:06:46.080 --> 01:06:48.960
if it were being carried out in a biased system.

01:06:49.680 --> 01:06:53.040
When Herrnstein and Murray say properly administered IQ tests

01:06:53.040 --> 01:06:54.880
are not demonstrably biased,

01:06:54.880 --> 01:06:57.360
they seemingly mean that the tests themselves

01:06:57.360 --> 01:06:59.920
do not contain words like regatta,

01:06:59.920 --> 01:07:03.600
not that the tests necessarily deliver fair results.

01:07:03.600 --> 01:07:07.440
So that is another potential problem with IQ tests to watch out for.

01:07:07.440 --> 01:07:11.600
Even if we eliminate as much cultural bias as possible from the test,

01:07:11.600 --> 01:07:13.920
we could still, thanks to the wider environment

01:07:13.920 --> 01:07:17.840
the tests are taking place in, be receiving biased results.

01:07:17.840 --> 01:07:20.400
For instance, if you carried out an IQ test

01:07:20.400 --> 01:07:23.920
in a racially segregated white supremacist state,

01:07:23.920 --> 01:07:27.440
that environment is obviously gonna affect the average IQ scores

01:07:27.440 --> 01:07:29.920
of different designated racial groups.

01:07:29.920 --> 01:07:31.120
Now you might protest.

01:07:31.120 --> 01:07:33.680
This also seems like a very obvious point.

01:07:33.680 --> 01:07:36.720
I mean, surely nobody's gonna carry out an IQ test

01:07:36.720 --> 01:07:39.680
in a racially segregated white supremacist state

01:07:39.680 --> 01:07:42.720
and then try to pass off those results as legitimate, right?

01:07:43.600 --> 01:07:45.840
Again, stay tuned, folks.

01:07:45.840 --> 01:07:48.720
Now keeping in mind all the various possible problems

01:07:48.720 --> 01:07:50.880
with IQ testing that we've just discussed,

01:07:50.880 --> 01:07:53.120
let's take a look at a few of the IQ tests

01:07:53.120 --> 01:07:57.600
that Herrnstein and Murray cite as evidence for claims in the bell curve.

01:07:57.600 --> 01:08:00.800
Surely they will be properly administered, right?

01:08:00.800 --> 01:08:02.960
After all, Herrnstein and Murray themselves

01:08:02.960 --> 01:08:05.840
discuss many of the same issues that we just have.

01:08:05.840 --> 01:08:08.160
It would follow that given their familiarity

01:08:08.160 --> 01:08:09.520
with these potential problems,

01:08:09.520 --> 01:08:12.320
they would of course endeavor to avoid them.

01:08:12.320 --> 01:08:14.560
So let's see how they do on that front.

01:08:15.120 --> 01:08:18.160
We'll take a look at a particular section of the bell curve now,

01:08:18.160 --> 01:08:19.360
see what the claims are,

01:08:19.360 --> 01:08:22.960
and then have a bit of a dig into the sources backing up those claims.

