Sometimes the entire set of variables is loaded into a single regression equation.

01:52:15.280 --> 01:52:19.760
Sometimes sets of equations are used, modeling even more complex relationships

01:52:19.760 --> 01:52:23.600
in which all the variables can exert mutual effects on one another.

01:52:23.600 --> 01:52:25.280
Why should we not press forward?

01:52:25.280 --> 01:52:30.480
Why not also ask if religious background has an effect on the decision to go on welfare, for example?

01:52:30.480 --> 01:52:34.880
It's an interesting question, as are 50 others that might come to mind.

01:52:34.880 --> 01:52:37.680
This is the first of two defenses by Hanstein and Murray,

01:52:37.680 --> 01:52:41.920
where they argue that it would just be too complicated to consider all the factors.

01:52:42.480 --> 01:52:48.000
Why there could be 50 environmental variables affecting someone's likelihood of being in poverty,

01:52:48.000 --> 01:52:49.600
that's just too many.

01:52:49.600 --> 01:52:51.200
It would be too complex.

01:52:51.200 --> 01:52:54.000
Our graph wouldn't make any sense if we did that.

01:52:54.000 --> 01:52:58.080
So instead of 50, we're just gonna consider, I don't know, two.

01:52:58.080 --> 01:53:01.200
This is a result of treating the method of investigation

01:53:01.200 --> 01:53:04.480
as more important than getting accurate results.

01:53:04.480 --> 01:53:08.240
If you can't use regression analysis to fairly compare IQ

01:53:08.240 --> 01:53:11.760
to all the relevant environmental factors, don't.

01:53:12.320 --> 01:53:14.880
You know, you don't actually have to do this.

01:53:15.440 --> 01:53:19.440
Hanstein and Murray's second defense is even more telling than the first.

01:53:20.080 --> 01:53:22.800
Our principle was to explore additional dynamics

01:53:22.800 --> 01:53:26.480
when there was another factor that was not only conceivably important,

01:53:26.480 --> 01:53:29.440
but for clear logical reasons might be important

01:53:29.440 --> 01:53:32.800
because of dynamics having little or nothing to do with IQ.

01:53:33.680 --> 01:53:35.440
This last proviso is crucial,

01:53:35.440 --> 01:53:38.560
for one of the most common misuses of regression analysis

01:53:38.560 --> 01:53:40.800
is to introduce an additional variable

01:53:40.800 --> 01:53:46.800
that in reality is mostly another expression of variables that are already in the equation.

01:53:46.800 --> 01:53:50.320
So what Hanstein and Murray are saying is that they dismissed variables

01:53:50.320 --> 01:53:54.480
if they deemed them to merely be mostly expressions of IQ,

01:53:54.480 --> 01:53:56.640
which is already in the equation.

01:53:57.440 --> 01:53:59.440
They only considered additional factors

01:53:59.440 --> 01:54:01.760
when they had little or nothing to do with IQ

01:54:01.760 --> 01:54:04.560
and were, quote, conceivably important.

01:54:04.560 --> 01:54:06.480
Which should lead us to ask a question.

01:54:06.480 --> 01:54:11.520
How are Hanstein and Murray deciding which variables are conceivably important?

01:54:11.520 --> 01:54:14.880
And how are they deciding how much they have to do with IQ?

01:54:14.880 --> 01:54:18.000
And the answer, of course, is subjectively.

01:54:18.000 --> 01:54:22.240
They're only considering things that they reckon are important.

01:54:22.240 --> 01:54:25.440
You see, the problem with Hanstein and Murray dismissing variables

01:54:25.440 --> 01:54:30.400
that they have subjectively decided are merely expressions of cognitive ability here

01:54:30.400 --> 01:54:36.000
is that they think that socioeconomic status itself is an expression of cognitive ability.

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:41.200
Later in the book, when criticizing the practice of controlling for SES between racial groups,

01:54:41.200 --> 01:54:41.920
they write,

01:54:41.920 --> 01:54:47.040
the difficulty comes in interpreting what it means to control for socioeconomic status.

01:54:47.040 --> 01:54:50.320
Matching the status of the groups is usually justified on the grounds

01:54:50.320 --> 01:54:55.440
that the scores people earn are caused to some extent by their socioeconomic status.

01:54:55.440 --> 01:54:59.360
So if we want to see the real or authentic difference between them,

01:54:59.360 --> 01:55:02.240
the contribution of status must be excluded.

01:55:02.240 --> 01:55:07.600
The trouble is that socioeconomic status is also a result of cognitive ability,

01:55:07.600 --> 01:55:09.680
as people of high and low cognitive ability

01:55:09.680 --> 01:55:13.760
move to correspondingly high and low places in the socioeconomic continuum.

01:55:13.760 --> 01:55:16.000
Now, this is circular logic.

01:55:16.000 --> 01:55:19.840
Hanstein and Murray claim to be limiting which factors they're considering

01:55:19.840 --> 01:55:24.240
to avoid including those which are merely expressions of other factors,

01:55:24.240 --> 01:55:29.600
but their main comparison here is between cognitive ability and socioeconomic status,

01:55:29.600 --> 01:55:33.760
which they elsewhere argue is a result of cognitive ability.

01:55:33.760 --> 01:55:40.000
Using this framework, where cognitive ability determines both IQ and socioeconomic status,

01:55:40.000 --> 01:55:43.120
the whole series of comparisons from this chapter of the bell curve

01:55:43.120 --> 01:55:45.440
seems cynical and unnecessary.

01:55:45.520 --> 01:55:50.000
Hanstein and Murray have already decided what conclusion they're gonna come to,

01:55:50.000 --> 01:55:54.080
that cognitive ability is more important than all the other variables,

01:55:54.080 --> 01:55:58.240
and all their statistical comparisons read as them just going through the motions

01:55:58.240 --> 01:55:59.680
to get that result.

01:55:59.680 --> 01:56:04.880
In simply declaring socioeconomic status the result of cognitive ability,

01:56:04.880 --> 01:56:08.720
the bell curve brings to mind the chicken and egg problem here.

01:56:09.280 --> 01:56:11.440
You see, a lot of disagreements over IQ

01:56:11.440 --> 01:56:14.960
stem from different interpretations of the same data.

01:56:14.960 --> 01:56:18.320
Let's say you do a study which proves a strong positive correlation

01:56:18.320 --> 01:56:22.720
between the amount of time someone has spent in education and their IQ,

01:56:22.720 --> 01:56:25.840
and you present those findings to two groups of people.

01:56:25.840 --> 01:56:28.720
One group that favors environmental explanations

01:56:28.720 --> 01:56:31.600
and one that favors genetic explanations.

01:56:31.600 --> 01:56:34.720
Now, of course, the environmentalists will say,

01:56:34.720 --> 01:56:36.960
this result makes perfect sense.

01:56:36.960 --> 01:56:39.840
The longer you're in education, the more things you learn,

01:56:39.840 --> 01:56:43.920
the better you get at answering the sorts of questions that show up on IQ tests,

01:56:43.920 --> 01:56:48.080
the more familiar you are with taking academic tests in the first place.

01:56:48.080 --> 01:56:51.200
IQ clearly stems from environment.

01:56:51.200 --> 01:56:54.240
The genetic-minded folks, on the other hand, will say,

01:56:54.240 --> 01:56:57.280
of course, this result makes perfect sense.

01:56:57.280 --> 01:57:00.480
People with higher IQs favor an academic environment,

01:57:00.480 --> 01:57:02.800
and they're more likely to stay in school longer

01:57:02.800 --> 01:57:05.200
because that's the smarter thing to do.

01:57:05.200 --> 01:57:07.680
Since they have higher IQs to begin with,

01:57:07.680 --> 01:57:09.920
they will naturally make better choices.

01:57:09.920 --> 01:57:13.280
Environment clearly stems from IQ.

01:57:13.280 --> 01:57:16.560
So which came first, the chicken or the egg?

01:57:16.560 --> 01:57:18.800
Environment or cognitive ability?

01:57:18.800 --> 01:57:20.800
We can phrase this two ways.

01:57:20.800 --> 01:57:24.320
A parent's higher cognitive ability leads to a better environment,

01:57:24.320 --> 01:57:28.080
which again leads to a higher cognitive ability in their children.

01:57:28.080 --> 01:57:30.240
Or we can say that a better environment

01:57:30.240 --> 01:57:32.560
leads to a parent's higher cognitive ability,

01:57:32.560 --> 01:57:35.920
which then produces a better environment for their children.

01:57:35.920 --> 01:57:38.720
But both of these ways of phrasing are merely presenting

01:57:38.720 --> 01:57:43.600
a segment of the overall environment-cognitive ability logic chain.

01:57:43.600 --> 01:57:46.160
The bell curve solves the conundrum of whether

01:57:46.160 --> 01:57:49.360
cognitive ability or environment should come first by saying...

01:57:50.080 --> 01:57:51.200
cognitive ability.

01:57:51.920 --> 01:57:52.720
That's first.

01:57:52.720 --> 01:57:56.080
We like that one the most, so that's the one that comes first.

01:57:56.080 --> 01:57:58.480
But of course, this is completely arbitrary,

01:57:58.480 --> 01:58:01.440
and also, ultimately, incorrect.

01:58:01.440 --> 01:58:05.120
To understand this, we need to talk about another of the main problems

01:58:05.120 --> 01:58:08.000
with the scientific arguments of the bell curve,

01:58:08.000 --> 01:58:11.920
which is that Herrnstein and Murray are conspicuously uninterested

01:58:11.920 --> 01:58:14.880
in the causes of the things that they're talking about.

01:58:15.840 --> 01:58:18.720
Much of the bell curve, for instance, is concerned with proving

01:58:18.720 --> 01:58:21.840
that there are substantial differences in cognitive ability

01:58:21.840 --> 01:58:24.400
between different designated racial groups.

01:58:24.400 --> 01:58:28.160
But what Herrnstein and Murray never seriously concern themselves with

01:58:28.160 --> 01:58:31.120
is why this supposed divergence happened.

01:58:31.120 --> 01:58:35.520
Population groups don't evolve to be different for no reason, do they?

01:58:35.520 --> 01:58:38.960
If one group developed better cognitive skills than another group,

01:58:38.960 --> 01:58:40.960
there would have to be some mechanism there

01:58:40.960 --> 01:58:44.400
that was leading to higher cognitive ability in that group,

01:58:44.400 --> 01:58:48.240
or, I suppose, leading to lower cognitive ability in the other group.

01:58:48.240 --> 01:58:51.280
Now, this could simply be direct evolutionary pressure,

01:58:51.280 --> 01:58:54.320
as in different levels of cognitive ability in different groups

01:58:54.320 --> 01:58:56.800
are being directly selected for.

01:58:56.800 --> 01:58:59.520
Or it could be an indirect, unintended effect

01:58:59.520 --> 01:59:01.680
of a different trait being selected for,

01:59:01.680 --> 01:59:03.840
or some sort of genetic drift,

01:59:03.840 --> 01:59:06.320
as generations of different population groups

01:59:06.320 --> 01:59:08.320
are isolated enough from each other

01:59:08.320 --> 01:59:11.360
to develop in significantly different ways.

01:59:11.360 --> 01:59:15.120
Whatever the reason, though, there would have to be a reason.

01:59:15.120 --> 01:59:18.080
And we should expect a scientist attempting to argue

01:59:18.080 --> 01:59:21.360
for a substantial difference in ability between different groups

01:59:21.360 --> 01:59:26.560
to therefore maybe be interested in exactly why this difference came about, right?

01:59:27.120 --> 01:59:29.520
One of the only times that Herrnstein and Murray

01:59:29.520 --> 01:59:31.440
show any interest in this question

01:59:31.440 --> 01:59:33.920
is in Appendix Five, where they discuss the work

01:59:33.920 --> 01:59:37.200
of Canadian psychologist J. Philippe Rushton,

01:59:37.200 --> 01:59:41.760
who wrote the book Race, Evolution, and Behavior in 1995.

